======================================================================
PART 7: 7 = Φ₃(2) — MEANING OF CYCLOTOMIC STRUCTURE
======================================================================

  WHY 7 = Φ₃(2):

  Φ₃(x) = x² + x + 1. At x=2: 4+2+1 = 7.

  The roots of Φ₃(x) are the primitive 3rd roots of unity: ω, ω².
  So 7 = (2-ω)(2-ω²) where ω = e^{2πi/3}.

  In F₇: since Φ₃(2) = 0 mod 7, we have 2²+2+1 ≡ 0 (mod 7).
  This means 2 is a primitive cube root of unity in F₇!
  Indeed: 2³ = 8 ≡ 1 (mod 7), and ord₇(2) = 3.

  For tournaments: H ≡ 1 (mod 2) always (Rédei).
  Since ord₇(2) = 3, the powers of 2 cycle through {1, 2, 4} mod 7.

  In the OCF: H = 1 + 2α₁ + 4α₂ + 8α₃ + ...
  Mod 7:      H ≡ 1 + 2α₁ + 4α₂ + 1·α₃ + 2α₄ + 4α₅ + ...  (mod 7)

  The coefficients cycle with period 3: {2, 4, 1, 2, 4, 1, ...}
  This is because 2³ ≡ 1 (mod 7), which IS the cyclotomic condition!

  Powers of 2 mod 7:
    2^0 = 1 ≡ 1 (mod 7)
    2^1 = 2 ≡ 2 (mod 7)
    2^2 = 4 ≡ 4 (mod 7)
    2^3 = 8 ≡ 1 (mod 7)
    2^4 = 16 ≡ 2 (mod 7)
    2^5 = 32 ≡ 4 (mod 7)
    2^6 = 64 ≡ 1 (mod 7)
    2^7 = 128 ≡ 2 (mod 7)
    2^8 = 256 ≡ 4 (mod 7)
    2^9 = 512 ≡ 1 (mod 7)

  Period = 3 = order of the cyclotomic polynomial Φ₃.
  The period-3 cycling means: H mod 7 depends only on
  (α₁ mod 7, α₂ mod 7, (α₁+α₂+α₃) mod 7, ...)

  COMPARISON WITH OTHER HIERARCHY PRIMES:
  3 = Φ₂(2): ord₃(2) = 2, period-2 cycling: {2,1,2,1,...}
  5 = Φ₄(2): ord₅(2) = 4, period-4 cycling: {2,4,3,1,...}
  7 = Φ₃(2): ord₇(2) = 3, period-3 cycling: {2,4,1,...}
  11= Φ₁₀(2): ord₁₁(2)= 10, period-10 cycling
  31= Φ₅(2): ord₃₁(2) = 5, period-5 cycling

  DEEP PATTERN: Φ_d(2) = p ↔ ord_p(2) = d
  The cyclotomic index d IS the multiplicative order of 2 mod p!
  This is NOT a coincidence — it's the definition of cyclotomic polynomials.

  TOURNAMENT MEANING:
  H mod p has OCF coefficients cycling with period d = ord_p(2).
  Shorter period = MORE constraints on H mod p.
  ord₃(2)=2: very constrained → only H≡1(mod2) survives
  ord₇(2)=3: 3-periodic → still quite constrained at small n
  ord₅(2)=4: 4-periodic → less constrained, but still interesting

======================================================================
PART 8: (5,6)-RECURRENCE CONNECTING I(2) AND I(3)
======================================================================

  Since I(x) = 1 + x·α₁ + x²·α₂ (at n=5), we have:

    I(2) = H = 1 + 2α₁ + 4α₂
    I(3) = 1 + 3α₁ + 9α₂

  So: I(3) - I(2) = α₁ + 5α₂
  And: 3·I(2) - 2·I(3) = 1 - 6α₂

  More generally, for the (5,6)-recurrence:
    x(n) = 5x(n-1) - 6x(n-2)  has roots 2, 3.

  Apply this to I(x) viewed as evaluating at x=2,3,4,...:
    I(x+1) = 5·I(x) - 6·I(x-1)?

  NO — I is a polynomial in x, not a linear recurrence in x.
  But we CAN write:
    I(x) = 1 + α₁·x + α₂·x² = quadratic in x

  Three evaluations determine it completely:
    I(0) = 1 (always)
    I(2) = H
    I(3) = (9H - 5 - 6α₁)/4  (from the formula)

  So I(x) is determined by (H, α₁), which is determined by
  any two evaluations at x ≠ 0.

  I(2)=H and I(3) determine all I(x) at n=5:

      H    α₁  I(2)  I(3)   I(5)   I(6)    I(7)    I(8)
      1     0     1     1      1      1       1       1
      3     1     3     4      6      7       8       9
      5     2     5     7     11     13      15      17
      9     4     9    13     21     25      29      33
     11     5    11    16     26     31      36      41
     15     7    15    22     36     43      50      57
     13     6    13    19     31     37      43      49

